<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-11-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-11-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="824" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d824">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Everett</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-11-14"><hi rend="italic">November 14,
                                    1900</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 294.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            dispatch, No. 454, of the 25th ultimo, quoting your telegram to the
                            minister for foreign affairs of Honduras insisting upon the prompt
                            payment of $10,000, gold, as indemnity in the Pears case, and also
                            quoting the minister’s reply.</p>
                        <p>Your action in the matter is approved by the President.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>